Buffs and Debuffs

A maximum of eight buffs and debuffs can be applied to enemies, while a maximum of six can be applied to allies.
Any more applied will remove the same number, starting with the oldest.
Silver-framed buffs and debuffs, however, cannot be removed by additions, and will persist regardless of the order in which they were applied.
Gold-framed buffs and debuffs also cannot be removed by additions, nor can they be removed by effects that would normally cancel them.
Precedence for applying buffs and debuffs of the same type is as follows.

1. For the same effect with different values, priority is given to the higher value.
E.g., if ATK +30% is already in effect, applying ATK +10% will not overwrite it.
2. For the same effect with equal values, priority is given to the one with more time remaining.
E.g., if ATK +30% is in effect with two turns left...
...applying ATK +30% with only one turn will not overwrite it, so two turns remain.
...applying ATK+30% with two turns will overwrite it, so again two turns remain.
...applying ATK+30% with three turns will also overwrite it, so now three turns remain.

While an enframed buff or debuff is in effect, if a higher value buff or debuff of the same effect is granted or inflicted, the effect will be overwritten by the higher value while maintaining its enframed status.

In the case of gold and silver frames, gold frames take priority.

E.g., if a gold-framed ATK Down 50% for 5 turns is in effect, inflicting ATK Down 70% for 3 turns that would normally have no frame will overwrite the original debuff with a gold-framed ATK Down 70% for 3 turns.
There are some statuses that effect a certain amount of HP damage but cannot inflict KO on their own; e.g., Exdeath's Curse debuff, and the BT effect from Absolute Power of the Void. Effects that increase or decrease HP damage have no influence on the HP damage effected by statuses such as these.
